We want to find:

\[\sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{k + 2}{k! + (k+1)! + (k+2)!}\]

First, let's try to simplify the denominator. Notice we can factor out a $(k+2)!$:

\begin{align*}
\frac{k+2}{k! + (k+1)! + (k+2)!} &= \frac{k+2}{(k+2)! \left( \frac{1}{(k+2)!} + \frac{k+1}{(k+2)!} + 1 \right)} \\
&= \frac{k+2}{(k+2)! \left( \frac{1 + k + 1}{(k+2)!} + 1 \right)} \\
&= \frac{k+2}{(k+2)! \left( \frac{k+2 + (k+2)!}{(k+2)!} \right)} \\
&= \frac{k+2}{(k+2 + (k+2)!)}
\end{align*}

Now, let's look at the partial sums:

\begin{align*}
S_n &= \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{k+2}{k! + (k+1)! + (k+2)!} \\
&= \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{k+2}{(k+2 + (k+2)!)} \\
&= \frac{3}{3 + 3!} + \frac{4}{4 + 4!} + \frac{5}{5 + 5!} + \dots + \frac{n+2}{n+2 + (n+2)!}
\end{align*}

We can rewrite each term as:

\begin{align*}
\frac{k+2}{k+2 + (k+2)!} &= \frac{1}{1 + \frac{(k+2)!}{k+2}} \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (k+1)!} - \frac{1}{1 + k!}
\end{align*}

Notice the pattern when we write out the full sum:

\begin{align*}
S_n &= \left( \frac{1}{1 + 2!} - \frac{1}{1 + 1!} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{1 + 3!} - \frac{1}{1 + 2!} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{1 + 4!} - \frac{1}{1 + 3!} \right) + \dots + \left( \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - \frac{1}{1 + (n+1)!} \right) \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - \frac{1}{1 + 1!} \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!} - 1
\end{align*}

As $n$ gets really big, the term $\frac{1}{1 + (n+2)!}$ gets smaller and smaller, approaching zero.  So, the sum converges to:

